In 1973, Steve Jobs was just a college student looking for a job. This application shows the earliest stage of his dream. Look at what he wrote in the “special abilities” category — “electronic tech & design engineer.” He knew his calling early on, even though he didn’t know all the steps to take at the time. Don’t rush the process. Take your time. Great things are headed your way.
Just a gentle reminder that there’s a difference being AVAILABLE & being FREE. 💫💯

As we mark the end of Black History Month, I want to celebrate a Black creative who inspires me.

It was the summer of 2021. @jaquelknight and I were paired up together as a dynamic ‘director & writer’ duo for a major project we were both passionate about. We’ve never met until this very moment, and were introduced on a zoom call.

From the moment our paths crossed, I was captivated by your dynamic creativity, your artistry as a director, your VISION, and how your confidence TOOK UP SPACE that it was worthy of all along… as a Black man, as a visual storyteller and as a necessary disruptor to the status quo.

Since working with you, it has helped me redefine my standard of excellence in the industry, my confidence, and empowered me to believe that my VIBE is a TALENT that just so happens to be part of my gift.

Thank you for your unapologetic authenticity and pushing the envelope for our narrative as a culture… one project & showcase at a time. 

Continue fighting through your milestone moments and keep breaking barriers to inspire a new generation of Black creatives. This post is a small gesture of appreciation. I hope to spark that audacity in others 🏁🖤

“It was a long time ago. 
I have almost forgotten my dream. 
But it was there then, 
In front of me, 
Bright like a sun— 
My dream. 
And then the wall rose, 
Rose slowly, 
Slowly, 
Between me and my dream. 
Rose until it touched the sky— 
The wall. 
Shadow. 
I am black. 
I lie down in the shadow. 
No longer the light of my dream before me, 
Above me. 
Only the thick wall. 
Only the shadow. 
My hands.
My dark hands.
Break through the wall.
Find my dream.
Help me to shatter this darkness, 
To smash this night, 
To break this shadow 
Into a thousand lights of sun, 
Into a thousand whirling dreams 
Of sun.” — Langston Hughes.

Ever looked at an image and it reminded you of a poem? In my mind, Africa is narrating this poem. The DREAM of Africa can be found through unity & love. Africa needs that now more then ever, to rediscover the motherland’s greatest potential. It’s even more beautiful when we, as children and descendants of the diaspora, share the same hopes and dreams for all of Africa 🖤🏁 #OneAfrica

We should never do the work for awards, but when it becomes award-winning work, it shines a light on the level of excellence that should always be the standard to pursue.

Honored to earn the @allwomeninmedia 2023 Gracie Award for Best Documentary alongside my talented colleagues, some of the best journalists in the industry.

‘A Different Cry’ is a docu-series that changed my life. And we hope it’s made a difference in this world.

dear baby cousin, you visited my dreams. and here i am, typing in all lowercase like you used to.

i catch myself re-reading our texts over and over again, just to relive you. life hasn’t been the same since you spiritually transitioned in january. but i know your final home always has a line of communication, through prayer. 

i keep wanting to hold you in my arms like i used to when you were a baby. when you learned to walk, i wanted to slow down your independence. always carrying you, so you could still rely on me. talk about attachment. 

you used to say i helped raise you, but you raised my standards on a life well-lived. there was so much love in your heart, grace in your care, and purpose in your soul. and that’s how I knew the presence of God radiated through your existence. when I told you “Allah loves you”, I really meant it. His love was visible in your hopes for better days. 

thank you for teaching me more about life than any textbook, more about grace than any deed, more about unconditional love than any movie, more about the power of hope than any answered prayer. and most importantly, thank you for teaching me about the art and beauty of ‘imperfect perfections’ {like basquiat’s art}  which is what we all are as human beings. & look how amazing his crowns look in our photo, as if it belongs there, like we’re completions of jean-michel’s craft.

may your love flow through my life as a reminder of your energy. a true sign of my healing journey, since losing you, has been to balance the longing for a revision… with prayers that protect your ever-lasting transition. now that’s proof that your love is eternal. 4life & beyond. can’t wait til you visit my dreams again.

My latest report for @11Alive: Bodycam video shows interactions between APD officers & youth selling water bottles.

11Alive obtained two body-worn camera videos and various incident reports from the Atlanta Police Department via public records requests. 

We wanted to know more about the the interactions youth and police have, as part of our continuing coverage of kids and teens’ lives in the city of Atlanta — from intervention, prevention, resources, mentorship, etc.

11Alive asked Atlanta Police for a sit down interview this summer to discuss public safety concerns, community outreach, handling youth involved with water sales, and more. The department declined multiple requests.

We reached out to NAACP Georgia chapter President and civil rights attorney @attorneygriggs to provide perspective.
